      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, that makes sense. i missed the delete on the buffer, i'll add that. \n\nbut even after i fixed that specific one, we're still seeing some very strange, intermittent spikes in memory usage that don't quite follow a linear pattern. it's like the leak only happens when certain sequences of interrupts occur. how do i hunt down those more \"hidden\" or non-obvious leaks that don't just happen every single time the function is called?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Intermittent spikes tied to interrupt sequences suggest the problem isn't a simple forgotten `delete`, but rather a race condition or a failure to clean up state *within* an interrupt service routine (ISR) or a deferred processing task triggered by an interrupt. These hidden leaks are often caused by dynamic allocation happening inside an ISR, which is generally unsafe, or by global/static resources not being properly reset after an asynchronous event.\n\nTo hunt these down, you need to instrument your code to log the memory state *around* the interrupt handlers. If you can't use a full profiler, log the heap usage (if your RTOS/toolchain allows reading heap statistics) immediately before and immediately after the critical interrupt sequence. Look for the delta spike.\n\nFurthermore, review any code paths that use dynamic allocation (`new`) that are called from, or are themselves called by, an ISR. If you are using dynamic memory management in an ISR, you are likely introducing non-deterministic behavior that leads to heap corruption, which *looks* like a leak until the system crashes or runs out of memory. A robust system should never allocate memory from an ISR; it should flag a request for a task to handle the allocation later.",
      "source": "target",
