    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When memory seems to be \"sneaking\" in and hiding, it often points toward fragmentation or objects that are being allocated but never properly destroyed, perhaps because the destruction logic is dependent on a state that is never reached. You should look for patterns related to object lifecycle management, not just raw byte counts.\n\nSpecifically, look for patterns involving:\n\n1.  **Circular References:** If you are using C++ smart pointers or custom object graphs, check for objects pointing to each other where neither has a clear owner to trigger destruction. This is a classic \"invisible\" leak.\n2.  **Static/Global Caches:** If you have any caches (e.g., a map storing recently processed packets), ensure that the eviction/cleanup logic is firing correctly under all operational loads, especially during high-interrupt scenarios.\n3.  **State Machines:** If your system uses complex state machines, ensure that when the system transitions *out* of a complex state, all resources specifically tied to that state are completely released.\n\nIf you are using a custom memory manager, look for memory blocks that are marked as \"in use\" but are not associated with any currently active object instance. This is the signature of a logically orphaned allocation.",
